  - key: '[주-D002] 감석(甘石) : '
    value: “위(魏)나라 석중부(石仲夫)와 제(齊)나라 감공(甘公)이 천문(天文)을 맡아보는 벼슬을 지냈다.” 하였는데, 《후한서》 천문지(天文志)에 보임. 그래서 후세에 천문학에 능숙한 자를 감석(甘石)이라 칭함.
  - key: '[주-D003] 백일 동안 돌아오지 않는다[十旬不返] : '
    value: 《서경》 오자지가(五子之歌)에, “태강(太康)이 위(位)를 계승하여 안일하고 나태함으로써 그 덕을 상실하니, 백성들이 모두 두 마음을 갖게 되었는데, 그는 반성하지 아니하고 절제없이 방종하여 낙수(洛水)의 밖에 사냥 나가 십순(十旬 백일)을 돌아오지 아니하였다.” 하였음.
  - key: '[주-D004] 긍경(肯䋜) : '
    value: 힘줄과 뼈가 결합한 곳을 말한 것임. 사물의 핵심이나 관건이 되는 부분의 비유.
  - key: '[주-D005] 연곡(輦轂) : '
    value: 임금이 타는 수레. 인하여 임금을 가리킴. 《한서(漢書)》 사마천전(司馬遷傳)에, “제가 선인(先人)의 유업을 힘입어 연곡 아래 대죄(待罪)한 것이 10여 년이라.” 하였음.
  - key: '[주-D006] 상빈(上賓) : '
    value: 도가(道家)에서 신선이 되어 하늘로 날아 올라간 것을 이름.
  - key: '[주-D007] 찬궁(欑宮) : '
    value: 제왕(帝王)의 빈궁(殯宮)을 칭한 것임. 《예기》 상복대기(喪服大記)에, “임금의 빈(殯)에는 순찬(輴欑)을 사용한다.” 하였다. 찬(欑)이란 뜻은 나무를 모아서 외부를 둘러 싼다는 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 초당(貂璫) : '
    value: 금초(金貂)ㆍ금당(金璫)을 합칭한 것인데, 환자(宦者)의 관식(冠飾)임. 그래서 세상이 환자를 칭하는 말로 씀. 《후한서》 주목전(朱穆傳)에, “주목이 몹시 환관을 미워하여 상소하였는데, 그 소에 이르기를, “한나라 고사를 살펴본즉 중상시(中常侍)가 사인(士人)을 고선(考選)하였는데, 건무(建武)시대 이후로는 전부 환자를 쓰기 시작하여 연평(延平)시대 이래로 더욱 귀성(貴盛)하였다. 그래서 초당(貂璫)의 위엄을 가식하여 상백(常伯)의 소임에 처하였다.” 하였음.
  - key: '[주-D009] 강은 민산(岷山)에서 나와서 차츰 커져[濫觴] : '
    value: 처음 시작은 심히 가늘다는 뜻임. 《가어(家語)》삼서(三恕)에, “무릇 강이 민산(岷山)에서 처음 나올 적에는 그 근원이 조그만한 술잔을 넘칠 만하다.” 하였음.
  - key: '[주-D010] 염락(濂洛)관민(關閩) : '
    value: 북송(北宋)으로부터 남송에 이르는 동안에 이학(理學)의 명유(名儒)로 염계(濂溪)의 주돈이(周敦頤), 낙양(洛陽)의 정호(程顥)ㆍ정이(程頤), 관중(關中)의 장재(張載), 민중(閩中)에 주희(朱熹)가 있어 염ㆍ낙ㆍ관ㆍ민의 사파(四派)라 칭한다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 수사(洙泗) : '
    value: 노(魯)나라 수수(洙水)ㆍ사수(泗水)를 말한 것임. 《예기》 단궁편(檀弓篇)에, “나는 너와 더불어 공부자를 수사(洙泗)의 사이에서 섬긴다.”[吾與女 事夫子於洙泗之間] 하였다.
english:
  title: Account of the Loyal and Righteous Duke
  author: Shin Jong-ho
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Duke's given name was Jong, courtesy name Jonggyeong, and he assumed the pen name Sangyoudang. His ancestors were from Kongam, now known as Yangcheon County.

    His remote ancestor, whose name was Seonmun, was a wealthy man of prominence in his village. When the founder of Goryeo campaigned against Baekje, this ancestor provided financial support for the military effort, and was rewarded with the title of Lord of Kongam Village. Eight generations back, his ancestor Gong served the king Chungryeol and rose to the position of Minister of State, becoming a renowned statesman of his time. The paternal grandfather was Geum, known by the pen name Yaedang—a man of broad learning and poetic talent who served as Minister of State in the late Goryeo, though he lived not long enough to fulfill the promise his virtue held, and people mourned this loss.

    From earliest youth, the Duke possessed a profound and expansive spirit, disdaining worldly trivialities. He closed his door to study, walking through life with eyes fixed downward, seeming lost in deep contemplation, so that none could fathom his inner nature. Sharing quarters with several companions, he showed remarkable equanimity when thieves one night stole all their belongings. Upon discovering the theft, while his friends lamented, the Duke calmly picked up a brush and wrote upon the wall: "Since they have taken my robes, they should have left my shoes."

    In the year Byungja of the Gyeongdae era, at age twenty-three, he passed the national examination. The following year, in Jeongchuk of the Cheonshun era, he again distinguished himself, placing third in the civil service examination. That day brought such drought that heaven and earth cried out for rain. When his name was called, the heavens themselves wept—so remarkable was his merit that the officials marveled, comparing him to the very rain itself sent by heaven.

    The Duke was appointed to various positions and assigned to study astronomy under the royal commission. His mastery of celestial calculations surpassed even those versed in ancient texts. When a solar eclipse occurred, he submitted his findings with a memorial advocating for six major reforms: the rejection of heterodoxy, the opening of remonstrance, the cessation of hunts, and the restoration of royal lectures among them—matters the throne had not wished to hear. When his bold remonstrance was brought before the king, the sovereign tested his mettle through increasingly harsh trials: feigned anger, the drawn sword, threats of execution. Yet the Duke remained unmoved, answering with perfect composure and eloquence. The king, seeing such unshakeable spirit, exclaimed, "A true man of valor!" and loaded him with honors and wine.

    The young sovereign, newly ascended, sought capable ministers to entrust with frontier affairs and to reform the realm. When he observed the Duke, his regard deepened daily. The Duke rose swiftly through increasingly important posts, eventually receiving command of armies in the northern reaches.

    When civil disturbances erupted in the northern provinces, the Duke was dispatched as commander. Learning of the rebellion, he spoke not of delay but of haste, saying, "It is like rescuing from fire and pulling from water. Would that I could ride a thousand miles in a day!" His steadfast courage restored order where it had fled. Though he fell gravely ill during the campaign, he would not rest, pushing forward until the rebels were defeated.

    During one crucial engagement, with the enemy entrenched on high ground raining arrows upon his forces, the Duke perceived a hidden path up a distant peak. Directing General Yu Yujo to scale it with a small force while he remained in the center, he rallied the main army. When the enemy saw the flags ascending the mountainside and heard the thunder of ten thousand voices, their formations collapsed. The rebel leader fled, and though pursued, the Duke ordered restraint, saying, "In my heart I have already bound this brigand. The followers who were forced to comply are the people's children. Must we slaughter them to achieve victory?"

    When the northern territories were pacified, the Duke was honored with the title of Minister and elevated to the highest ranks. Yet he took no pleasure in wealth, living simply in modest quarters. He received no private visitors at his gate, saying, "Fortune and rank rest with heaven. Why should I strive for them through crooked means?"

    His next great mission came when the northern tribes stirred again with warlike intent. The sovereign entrusted him with twenty thousand elite troops. Before his departure, the king presented him with a sword and addressed him personally: "Since ancient times, from the exploits of the Yellow Emperor to the campaigns of Han Wu, strong leadership has united the realm. The task I give you is not from love of conquest but from necessity. You possess both the civil and martial virtues required. Go forth and restore order to those distant reaches."

    The Duke's campaign was remarkable for its swift decisiveness and surprising victories. Enemies who thought themselves secure found themselves surrounded. The northern peoples, witnessing the vast host descending upon them like retribution from heaven itself, lost all will to resist. Snow fell upon the expedition, threatening to bury them, yet the Duke, speaking with such conviction of heaven's justice, seemed to call down clear skies by the force of his faith alone.

    Returning victorious, he was appointed to the highest councils of state. Yet even in power, he remained his authentic self—a man of unshakeable principle. When the sovereign considered unjust measures, the Duke alone spoke against them with such moral force that the king yielded. He advocated for education and virtue in the training of princes. He remonstrated against the frivolous abandonment of sacred ceremonies.

    When Chinese envoys visited with demands and pride, seeking to humiliate the kingdom, the Duke's mere presence transformed the encounter. His towering form, his measured dignity, his vast learning—so evident in his discourse on geography and history—commanded such respect that men who came in arrogance departed in reverence. Through patient reasoning and moral clarity, he secured favorable terms that would have seemed impossible.

    Throughout his life, the Duke embodied a rare synthesis of talents: scholar and warrior, administrator and sage. His appearance was imposing—tall, broad-browed, with a magnificent beard—yet his manner was warm as spring wind and clear as fair weather. He inspired awe without words and obedience without commands.

    He loved his people as a father loves his children. He studied the vast repositories of learning with such depth that nothing lay beyond his mastery—astronomy, geography, medicine, mathematics, all subjects were transparent to his penetrating mind. Yet his deepest learning was in the philosophy of human nature, wherein he attained a clarity and independence of vision that transcended mere scholarship.

    For more than thirty years, the weight of the nation rested upon his shoulders. His virtues were woven into the fabric of the realm's greatest achievements. When at last he fell ill, the sovereign sent his own physicians with precious medicines and the finest foods. The Duke's final words to his king, though barely audible, expressed his deepest wish: "May you guard the end as you guarded the beginning."

    When news came that he had passed, the court suspended its proceedings for three days. The king, hearing that the great minister had worn himself to death in service to the state, refused even to eat meat, saying, "How can I take sustenance when such a one has labored himself to dust in service to me?" The entire scholar-official class wept openly, and the realm felt orphaned.

    The Duke left three sons and one daughter, along with a legacy of deeds that would illuminate generations yet unborn. Like the great statesmen of old—Pei Du, Han Qi, and Zhang Jun—he stands as a model of how virtue and ability, joined with unflinching loyalty, can sustain a realm and elevate the human spirit. The pillar that bore up heaven has fallen, but its light endures in stone and silk, unchanging and eternal.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'rain itself sent by heaven' alludes to the ancient practice of crediting exceptional ministers with heaven-sent blessings, connecting the Duke's merit to celestial approval.
  - key: ''
    value: The Duke's refusal to use his high position for personal gain reflects the Confucian ideal of the gentleman-scholar (seonbi) who serves the state through moral exemplary rather than for material reward.
  - key: ''
    value: His mastery of diverse fields—astronomy, geography, medicine, mathematics, and above all moral philosophy—represents the ideal of the complete person valued in Korean Confucian tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The encounter with Chinese envoys illustrates a persistent theme in East Asian diplomatic history: the contest for prestige and proper protocol between tributary states and the imperial center.'
